{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479936"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:34:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:34:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20984"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20984"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.44,0.08,0.37,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13859"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100510"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13859"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20984"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82927"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"645"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"13336"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33466"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34347"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44238"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100510"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent. The parent reports that the child inserted a small plastic bead into his right nostril approximately one hour ago. The child is otherwise well. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A small blue plastic bead is visible in the right nasal cavity, approximately 1 cm from the nostril opening. There is no bleeding, discharge, or signs of distress.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Positive pressure via bag-valve-mask","Nasal forceps removal","Immediate referral to emergency department","Mother\u0027s kiss technique","Nasal irrigation with normal saline"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a common paediatric presentation of a nasal foreign body in a three-year-old child. The foreign body is clearly visible, has been present for a relatively short time, and there are no complications such as bleeding or significant distress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMother\u0027s kiss technique\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line management for this scenario. This non-invasive technique, with high level evidence (NHMRC Level 1 evidence), involves having the parent create a seal over the child\u0027s mouth (similar to mouth-to-mouth resuscitation), occlude the unaffected nostril, and deliver a short puff of air which passes through the nasopharynx and out through the affected nostril, potentially expelling the foreign body. This technique has a success rate of approximately 60% and should be performed under medical supervision. Despite theoretical risks such as barotrauma to the tympanic membranes and lower airways, there has never been a reported incidence of tympanic membrane rupture or pneumothorax using this technique.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasal forceps removal\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive technique that may cause distress to the child and potentially push the foreign body further into the nasal cavity. It may be considered if the mother\u0027s kiss technique is unsuccessful. The main danger in removing a nasal foreign body by any technique is aspiration, particularly in an uncooperative child.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive pressure via bag-valve-mask\u003C/strong\u003E applies a similar principle to the mother\u0027s kiss technique but is less controlled and may deliver excessive pressure, increasing the risk of complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasal irrigation with normal saline\u003C/strong\u003E might be helpful for organic materials or to clear mucus, but is unlikely to be effective for a solid plastic bead. It may also cause distress to the child and risks pushing the foreign body further into the nasal cavity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate referral to emergency department\u003C/strong\u003E would be necessary if the foreign body was a disk battery (due to risk of tissue necrosis), if there were signs of respiratory distress, or if the foreign body could not be visualised or removed after reasonable attempts in primary care. In this case, with a visible plastic bead and no complications, immediate referral is not necessary as the first step.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The mother\u0027s kiss technique is an effective first-line intervention for nasal foreign bodies in children, with success rates of approximately 60%.","The technique involves a parent creating a seal over the child\u0027s mouth, occluding the unaffected nostril, and delivering a short puff of air to expel the foreign body.","Button batteries in the nose require immediate emergency department referral due to risk of tissue necrosis."],"references":["RACGP Handbook of Non-Drug Interventions: Mother\u2019s kiss: nasal foreign bodies. Accessed at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/handi/a-z/m/mother-s-kiss-nasal-foreign-bodies","Purohit N, Ray S, Wilson T \u0026 Chawla OP. The \u2018Parent\u2019s Kiss\u2019: An Effective Way to Remove Paediatric Nasal Foreign Bodies. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2008 July; 90(5): 420\u2013422. doi: 10.1308/003588408X300966","Cook SC, Burton DM \u0026 Glasziou P. Efficacy and safety of the \u201cmother\u2019s kiss\u201d technique: a systematic review of the case reports and case series. CMAJ 2012. DOI:10.1503/cmaj.111864"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82927"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20984"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82927"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-26T06:51:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-26T06:52:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13859"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100510"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\